            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What is luminosity?</h2>
              <p>
                In astronomy, <strong>luminosity</strong> is the total power
                emitted by an object in the form of electromagnetic radiation.
                It is an intrinsic property, usually measured in watts (W) or in
                units of the Sun’s luminosity \(L_\odot\).
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on <em>astronomical luminosity</em> (not
                the psychological “brain training” brand or the general
                dictionary sense of “brightness”). It lets you move easily
                between:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Apparent magnitude \(m\)</li>
                <li>Absolute magnitude \(M\)</li>
                <li>Luminosity \(L\) and \(L/L_\odot\)</li>
                <li>Flux \(F\) at Earth or another distance</li>
                <li>Radius and effective temperature of a star</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Key formulas used</h2>

              <h3>1. Distance modulus: from apparent to absolute magnitude</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ m - M = 5 \log_{10}\left(\frac{d}{10\ \text{pc}}\right) \]
                </p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(m\) = apparent magnitude</li>
                  <li>\(M\) = absolute magnitude (magnitude at 10 pc)</li>
                  <li>\(d\) = distance in parsecs</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Rearranged:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ M = m - 5 \log_{10}\left(\frac{d}{10\ \text{pc}}\right) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Luminosity from absolute magnitude</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \frac{L}{L_\odot} = 10^{0.4\,(M_\odot - M)} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(L\) = luminosity of the object</li>
                  <li>\(L_\odot\) = luminosity of the Sun</li>
                  <li>
                    \(M_\odot\) = absolute magnitude of the Sun in the same band
                    (default 4.83 in V‑band)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Once \(L/L_\odot\) is known, the absolute luminosity is:</p>
                <p>\[ L = \frac{L}{L_\odot} \times L_\odot \]</p>
                <p>with \(L_\odot \approx 3.828 \times 10^{26}\ \text{W}\).</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Luminosity from flux and distance</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ F = \frac{L}{4\pi d^2} \quad \Rightarrow \quad L = 4\pi d^2
                  F \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(F\) = observed flux (W/m²)</li>
                  <li>\(d\) = distance (m)</li>
                  <li>\(L\) = luminosity (W)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>
                4. Luminosity from radius and temperature (Stefan–Boltzmann law)
              </h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ L = 4\pi R^2 \sigma T^4 \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(R\) = radius of the star (m)</li>
                  <li>\(T\) = effective temperature (K)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(\sigma = 5.670374419\times10^{-8}\ \text{W
                    m}^{-2}\text{K}^{-4}\) = Stefan–Boltzmann constant
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked example: luminosity of a bright star</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose a star has apparent magnitude \(m = 1.0\) and is at a
                distance of \(d = 100\ \text{pc}\).
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Compute absolute magnitude: \[ M = 1.0 - 5\log_{10}(100/10) =
                  1.0 - 5\log_{10}(10) = 1.0 - 5 = -4.0 \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  With \(M_\odot = 4.83\): \[ \frac{L}{L_\odot} = 10^{0.4(4.83 -
                  (-4.0))} = 10^{0.4 \times 8.83} \approx 10^{3.532} \approx
                  3400 \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  So the star is about 3,400 times more luminous than the Sun.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is luminosity the same as brightness?</h3>
              <p>
                Not exactly. <strong>Luminosity</strong> is the total power
                emitted by the object. <strong>Brightness</strong> (or flux) is
                how much of that power reaches an observer per unit area. A very
                luminous star can look faint if it is far away.
              </p>

              <h3>What units does this calculator use?</h3>
              <p>
                Internally, luminosity is computed in watts (W), distances in
                meters, and flux in W/m². For convenience, results are also
                expressed in units of the Sun’s luminosity \(L_\odot\).
              </p>

              <h3>Why do astronomers still use magnitudes?</h3>
              <p>
                The magnitude system is historical but convenient: differences
                in magnitude correspond to ratios of brightness on a logarithmic
                scale. A difference of 5 magnitudes corresponds to a factor of
                100 in brightness.
              </p>

              <h3>What about bolometric corrections?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool treats magnitudes as if they are already in the band
                you care about (e.g. bolometric or V‑band). For precise work you
                would apply a <em>bolometric correction</em> to convert from a
                band‑limited magnitude to a bolometric magnitude before using
                the luminosity formulas.
              </p>
